1
00:00:11,972 --> 00:00:15,267
I don't know.
Is this, like... Is it too 2010?

2
00:00:15,350 --> 00:00:16,893
Oh, seriously, babe,
it is not the clothes.

3
00:00:16,935 --> 00:00:19,771
Nobody cares how a person is dressed
in a job interview.

4
00:00:19,854 --> 00:00:22,315
Kirk Friedkin is just,
you know, excited to meet you.

5
00:00:22,399 --> 00:00:24,067
That's so easy for a man to say.

6
00:00:24,150 --> 00:00:26,653
- Oh, boy. I'm about to get womansplained.
- Yeah, you are.

7
00:00:26,736 --> 00:00:31,324
We get dissected for every wardrobe
choice. From our shoes to our lipstick.

8
00:00:31,408 --> 00:00:34,202
This has to say "assertive,
but not too assertive.

9
00:00:34,286 --> 00:00:37,330
Strong but, not too strong.
Confident, but not too confident."

10
00:00:37,414 --> 00:00:38,248
Does this say that?

11
00:00:38,331 --> 00:00:41,710
Yes. It says, "young Angela Merkel."

12
00:00:41,793 --> 00:00:42,877
- Don't say that again.
- Come on!

13
00:00:42,919 --> 00:00:44,587
She is the most powerful woman
in the world.

14
00:00:44,629 --> 00:00:46,423
I'm going shopping.
All my clothes are old.

15
00:00:46,506 --> 00:00:47,966
You should've said Bella Hadid.

16
00:00:48,466 --> 00:00:50,260
Jesus.
How long have you been standing there?

17
00:00:50,343 --> 00:00:52,137
I don't know. A while.

18
00:00:57,142 --> 00:00:58,143
She's too quiet.

19
00:00:58,226 --> 00:01:01,605
- She's gonna walk in on us one day.
- I know. It's almost like she wants to.

20
00:01:06,818 --> 00:01:10,488
Hmm. It's a suit.

21
00:01:11,072 --> 00:01:12,115
I...

22
00:01:12,198 --> 00:01:13,283
That's a good thing.

23
00:01:14,034 --> 00:01:15,243
No?

24
00:01:16,745 --> 00:01:18,622
Okay. That is also a suit.

25
00:01:18,705 --> 00:01:20,749
Is it too Angela Merkel?

26
00:01:20,832 --> 00:01:21,833
Totally.

27
00:01:22,959 --> 00:01:23,960
Who is that?

28
00:01:25,670 --> 00:01:27,255
This is a trick question, right?
Same suit?

29
00:01:27,297 --> 00:01:29,883
This costs four times
as much as the other ones.

30
00:01:29,966 --> 00:01:32,302
- Well, then you have to buy that one.
- Right?

31
00:01:32,385 --> 00:01:33,803
Does it come with the shirt?

32
00:01:38,516 --> 00:01:40,185
It's amazing, right?

33
00:01:40,268 --> 00:01:41,228
It's a suit.

34
00:01:42,354 --> 00:01:43,355
I deserve that.

35
00:01:45,106 --> 00:01:46,107
I'm sorry.

36
00:01:55,951 --> 00:01:56,952
[sighs]

37
00:02:05,544 --> 00:02:07,003
Sylvia Greeves?

38
00:02:07,087 --> 00:02:08,087
Yes.

39
00:02:10,549 --> 00:02:12,092
- [receptionist] Right this way.
- Hi.

40
00:02:12,175 --> 00:02:13,677
- Nice to meet you.
- You too.

41
00:02:13,760 --> 00:02:15,929
And how long have you been working here?

42
00:02:16,012 --> 00:02:17,847
["Work Bitch" playing]

43
00:02:31,027 --> 00:02:32,654
[phone ringing]

44
00:02:33,154 --> 00:02:34,948
Oh, my God. It's Kirk Friedkin.

45
00:02:35,031 --> 00:02:36,658
- Answer it.
- I'm too scared.

46
00:02:36,741 --> 00:02:38,118
Pick it up.

47
00:02:38,201 --> 00:02:40,521
Hello, Sylvia Greeves speaking.
How may I direct your call?

48
00:02:43,123 --> 00:02:45,667
Oh, yes. Hello, Kirk.
Nice to see... hear from you.

49
00:02:45,750 --> 00:02:47,043
Um, great to hear your voice.

50
00:02:50,338 --> 00:02:54,801
Oh, wow! That's so thrilling.
I'm absolutely...

51
00:02:54,885 --> 00:02:57,387
Thank you so much.
I can't wait to work with you next week.

52
00:02:57,470 --> 00:02:59,180
[chuckling] Okay. All the best.

53
00:03:01,141 --> 00:03:05,103
- I got the job! I got the job!
- [screams] Oh! Congratulations!

54
00:03:05,186 --> 00:03:07,439
- I'm so proud of you!
- [chuckles] Thank you!

55
00:03:07,522 --> 00:03:11,776
I'm so jealous. The best part of getting
a job is the time right before you start.

56
00:03:11,860 --> 00:03:15,113
You don't have the stress of getting it,
but you don't have to actually do the job.

57
00:03:15,155 --> 00:03:18,491
Well, I'm not there yet. I have so much
to organize before I even start work.

58
00:03:18,575 --> 00:03:21,035
I have to find someone to look after
the kids, drive them around

59
00:03:21,077 --> 00:03:23,288
and sign them up
for every after school thing, you know?

60
00:03:23,371 --> 00:03:24,456
It's a big transition.

61
00:03:24,539 --> 00:03:25,957
- [gasps]
- What?

62
00:03:26,041 --> 00:03:27,500
You're gonna leave me for the office moms,

63
00:03:27,542 --> 00:03:30,462
- 'cause you'll be one of them.
- Oh! How dare you. I would never.

64
00:03:30,545 --> 00:03:32,797
- If you break up with me…
- Here we go.

65
00:03:32,881 --> 00:03:35,300
- …I will end up on heroin.
- [gasps]

66
00:03:35,383 --> 00:03:37,761
You will find me lying
in a shelled-out building…

67
00:03:37,844 --> 00:03:39,012
- Mm-hmm.
- …on a cold, dirty floor,

68
00:03:39,054 --> 00:03:41,640
- covered in Taco Bell wrappers.
- Ooh, Taco Bell.

69
00:03:41,723 --> 00:03:42,849
This story has a happy ending.

70
00:03:42,891 --> 00:03:44,017
- Oh, I guess it does.
- Mmm.

71
00:03:48,188 --> 00:03:50,190
- [intercom buzzes]
- Hello?

72
00:03:50,273 --> 00:03:55,487
[imitates Dracula] Hello. This is Dracula.
I'm here for a booty call.

73
00:03:55,570 --> 00:03:56,863
Um, no, thanks.

74
00:03:56,947 --> 00:03:58,781
[normal voice]
Not actually Dracula. It's Will.

75
00:03:58,823 --> 00:04:00,533
How's it going? Wanna, uh, buzz me in?

76
00:04:00,617 --> 00:04:02,452
I'm not super psyched
to see you right now.

77
00:04:02,535 --> 00:04:04,496
- Why not?
- Maybe this rings a bell:

78
00:04:04,579 --> 00:04:09,042
Our relationship is "nothing,"
and I'm "not even worth mentioning."

79
00:04:09,125 --> 00:04:10,210
Who told you I said that?

80
00:04:10,293 --> 00:04:13,129
I'm friends with Omar. That's why
I was at your bar in the first place.

81
00:04:13,213 --> 00:04:15,215
Is that how you talk about me
with all your friends?

82
00:04:15,257 --> 00:04:18,218
No, my friends know how much I like you
and how much I care about you.

83
00:04:18,300 --> 00:04:20,720
- It was just a weird night.
- Weird how?

84
00:04:20,804 --> 00:04:24,307
Weird in that my f-friend was there,
and she's a pain in the ass,

85
00:04:24,391 --> 00:04:26,309
and I... I hadn't told her about you yet.

86
00:04:26,393 --> 00:04:27,310
Her?

87
00:04:27,394 --> 00:04:30,981
Yeah, my friend Sylvia.
[stammers] She's an old friend.

88
00:04:31,064 --> 00:04:33,567
She's happily married.
She has three children. Okay?

89
00:04:33,650 --> 00:04:35,527
Wow, she's really pretty.

90
00:04:35,610 --> 00:04:37,290
- How do you know that?
- I'm on her Insta.

91
00:04:37,362 --> 00:04:38,947
Already? How did you do that?

92
00:04:39,030 --> 00:04:40,031
She looks like a model.

93
00:04:40,115 --> 00:04:43,034
Look, can I come in and we can
just talk about this in person? Hello?

94
00:04:43,827 --> 00:04:44,828
Hello?

95
00:04:44,911 --> 00:04:47,163
[intercom buzzing]

96
00:04:56,756 --> 00:04:58,717
Bye. Oh, bye.

97
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:00,176
- Bye. Have a great trip, babe.
- I will.

98
00:05:00,218 --> 00:05:01,636
- I love you.
- Bye.

99
00:05:01,720 --> 00:05:02,679
Bye, Daddy.

100
00:05:02,762 --> 00:05:06,600
Oh, don't give Jessipa too much
sweet potato. It tends to back her up.

101
00:05:06,683 --> 00:05:07,642
Have fun!

102
00:05:07,726 --> 00:05:09,477
Who's ready to rock the Marriott Suites?

103
00:05:09,561 --> 00:05:13,940
All right. Don't worry. I'm here to
chaperone. There's one adult on the trip.

104
00:05:14,524 --> 00:05:15,442
Glad to hear it.

105
00:05:15,525 --> 00:05:18,236
[laughs] You're hilarious!

106
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:20,030
[chuckles] That was not a joke.

107
00:05:21,740 --> 00:05:23,032
I can't tell you how much it means

108
00:05:23,074 --> 00:05:26,202
that you're gonna help out
with pick-ups and afternoons,

109
00:05:26,286 --> 00:05:28,486
just while I get back into
the work swing of the things.

110
00:05:28,538 --> 00:05:30,582
Oh, that's what Nana's here for.
Right, Maevy?

111
00:05:30,665 --> 00:05:32,083
And we're gonna have such a good time.

112
00:05:32,125 --> 00:05:36,254
We actually don't usually have
this much sugar before dinner. [chuckles]

113
00:05:36,338 --> 00:05:39,799
That's her third lollipop. But, uh,
you know, just on special occasions.

114
00:05:39,883 --> 00:05:43,595
Well, every day's about to be
a special occasion. Isn't it? [chuckles]

115
00:05:43,678 --> 00:05:45,263
Yeah, we're just worried about her teeth.

116
00:05:45,305 --> 00:05:48,225
But, um, pick-up is 3:00 p.m.,

117
00:05:48,308 --> 00:05:51,061
but the carpool line
doesn't start until 2:55.

118
00:05:51,144 --> 00:05:53,313
[gasps]
This is a paella I made with real shrimp.

119
00:05:53,396 --> 00:05:58,568
Oh, and this is Lin-Manuel Miranda
in the grocery store. He-He's very polite.

120
00:05:58,652 --> 00:06:01,863
And the sign-out code I mentioned
on the app, Kinderlime,

121
00:06:01,947 --> 00:06:05,825
is 6235-Greeves&.

122
00:06:05,909 --> 00:06:09,329
And there's a separate sign-out code for,
um, Frances,

123
00:06:09,412 --> 00:06:11,248
for the a cappella choir rehearsal.

124
00:06:11,331 --> 00:06:14,834
And this is a fabulous straw hat
you can pack in a suitcase,

125
00:06:14,918 --> 00:06:16,711
and it just pops right back.

126
00:06:16,795 --> 00:06:18,547
Are you gonna write this down, Marla?

127
00:06:18,630 --> 00:06:20,340
Or do you want me
to send it to you in an e-mail?

128
00:06:20,382 --> 00:06:23,343
- Mommy is such a worrier!
- [phone buzzes]

129
00:06:24,135 --> 00:06:27,430
- Okay. Um, I'll be... I'll be one second.
- [phone buzzes]

130
00:06:27,514 --> 00:06:30,183
- Oh, my God.
- Yeah. What is it? Are you dead?

131
00:06:30,267 --> 00:06:32,769
Hey! No, you know how you wanted,
uh, to meet my girlfriend?

132
00:06:32,852 --> 00:06:34,187
- Can you come meet her now?
- Now?

133
00:06:34,229 --> 00:06:35,814
Yeah. How fast can you get to the bar?

134
00:06:35,897 --> 00:06:37,357
I'm really busy. I'm really sorry.

135
00:06:37,440 --> 00:06:40,110
Charlie just left on a trip.
My mother-in-law is here.

136
00:06:40,193 --> 00:06:42,779
I'm trying to get organized
because I start work on Monday.

137
00:06:42,862 --> 00:06:44,239
Because I got the job!

138
00:06:44,322 --> 00:06:45,990
I wouldn't ask
if it wasn't very important.

139
00:06:46,032 --> 00:06:49,035
"Oh! Congratulations, Sylvia.
You got the job!"

140
00:06:49,119 --> 00:06:50,912
Thank you, Will. You're such a good buddy.

141
00:06:50,996 --> 00:06:53,248
I am in deep fucking shit with Peyton.

142
00:06:53,331 --> 00:06:56,084
She found out that I said she was nothing
and the relationship was nothing.

143
00:06:56,126 --> 00:06:57,419
- I-I-It's bad.
- [stammers]

144
00:06:57,502 --> 00:06:59,546
How many dates
have you gone on with this girl?

145
00:06:59,629 --> 00:07:01,349
A few. Uh,
we have a very strong connection.

146
00:07:01,423 --> 00:07:02,924
- Well, that's something.
- It is something.

147
00:07:02,966 --> 00:07:05,510
No! It's nothing! Call me in a year
if you're still together.

148
00:07:05,594 --> 00:07:07,220
I-I have to get back
to my real life right now.

149
00:07:07,262 --> 00:07:09,764
She's not like that!
She's an old soul. You'll see.

150
00:07:09,848 --> 00:07:12,517
I need you right now. She thinks it's
weird that we spend so much time together

151
00:07:12,559 --> 00:07:14,039
and that I didn't tell you about her.

152
00:07:14,102 --> 00:07:17,647
And she is right. It is weird,
and I'm trying to "unweird" the situation.

153
00:07:17,731 --> 00:07:21,067
So, will you please just forgive me,
and just come here and help me out?

154
00:07:21,151 --> 00:07:23,194
Do you remember how I said
I had a job starting on Monday?

155
00:07:23,236 --> 00:07:24,756
Well, I have a job starting on Monday!

156
00:07:24,821 --> 00:07:28,783
Look, I'll say it. I want you to meet her,
because I care about your opinion.

157
00:07:28,867 --> 00:07:30,994
It's actually the opinion
I care about more than anything,

158
00:07:31,036 --> 00:07:32,954
so will you just come meet her?

159
00:07:33,038 --> 00:07:36,124
[gasps] Maeve, this is Nana's friend,
Marjorie's son, Peter.

160
00:07:36,207 --> 00:07:39,461
He's very successful
and owns his own dermatology practice.

161
00:07:39,544 --> 00:07:41,963
Okay, fine.
But this is dumb, and you owe me one.

162
00:07:45,926 --> 00:07:47,761
- Hey. There she is.
- [Sylvia] Hi.

163
00:07:47,844 --> 00:07:49,221
[exclaims]

164
00:07:49,304 --> 00:07:50,639
Hi!

165
00:07:50,722 --> 00:07:52,849
- [chuckles] Oh, hi!
- [chuckling]

166
00:07:54,434 --> 00:07:56,603
- Hi.
- You guys are hitting it off already.

167
00:07:57,312 --> 00:07:58,396
What can I get you to drink?

168
00:07:58,438 --> 00:08:00,857
Uh, just, um, your least gross beer.

169
00:08:00,941 --> 00:08:02,776
- Cool. You?
- Yum.

170
00:08:02,859 --> 00:08:04,611
- Whatever you think I'll like.
- Awesome.

171
00:08:04,694 --> 00:08:07,280
- Have a seat in the VIP table right there.
- Ooh. [chuckles]

172
00:08:07,364 --> 00:08:08,865
Um, I'm very... Uh, I'll be back.

173
00:08:08,949 --> 00:08:11,785
- Okay. [chuckles]
- "Reserved." [chuckles]

174
00:08:11,868 --> 00:08:12,994
Fancy.

175
00:08:15,247 --> 00:08:18,583
- [chuckles]
- Hey. [chuckles, sighs]

176
00:08:19,584 --> 00:08:22,254
So, where are you...
Where are you from, Peyton?

177
00:08:22,337 --> 00:08:26,174
I'm from this town outside Denver
called Columbine. Have you heard of it?

178
00:08:27,259 --> 00:08:28,635
- I have.
- Really?

179
00:08:28,718 --> 00:08:29,844
Mm-hmm.

180
00:08:31,179 --> 00:08:32,722
[both chuckle]

181
00:08:33,640 --> 00:08:35,058
Will's ladies, huh?

182
00:08:35,140 --> 00:08:38,602
Ugh, I really don't have time
for your weird bullshit right now.

183
00:08:38,687 --> 00:08:40,230
Fair enough. Maybe another time.

184
00:08:40,313 --> 00:08:41,356
Yeah.

185
00:08:41,438 --> 00:08:43,817
And, um, how did you meet Will?

186
00:08:43,900 --> 00:08:46,903
Oh, my God. It's a really funny story.

187
00:08:46,987 --> 00:08:50,365
- Oh, yeah?
- So, my friend Omar works here.

188
00:08:50,448 --> 00:08:51,348
Mm-hmm.

189
00:08:52,325 --> 00:08:54,327
- [chuckles]
- [chuckles]

190
00:08:55,495 --> 00:08:58,748
Aw. And what, uh...
What do you do for a living?

191
00:08:58,832 --> 00:09:01,376
I actually used to nanny
for this family back in Colorado

192
00:09:01,459 --> 00:09:03,378
with two little girls, Kenzie and Kayden.

193
00:09:03,461 --> 00:09:06,840
They're in middle school now.
[sighs] We text all the time.

194
00:09:06,923 --> 00:09:08,258
Aw. That's so cute.

195
00:09:08,341 --> 00:09:09,676
Yeah. [chuckles]

196
00:09:11,219 --> 00:09:13,597
And what... what do you do now?
What's your...

197
00:09:13,680 --> 00:09:17,642
I babysit here and there. Yeah, kids are
my passion. I'm a kid at heart. [chuckles]

198
00:09:17,726 --> 00:09:20,395
- Yes. Well...
- [chuckles] I wanna be a teacher.

199
00:09:20,478 --> 00:09:23,523
I'm actually going back to get
my Master's in Education in the fall.

200
00:09:23,607 --> 00:09:26,192
Oh, that's great.
I'm actually going back to work,

201
00:09:26,276 --> 00:09:28,611
and I'm looking for a babysitter
other than my mother-in-law.

202
00:09:28,653 --> 00:09:30,446
- [Peyton] Oh, my God.
- If you have any openings...

203
00:09:30,488 --> 00:09:33,742
- Love to. Yes. Oh, my...
- Okay. Oh, I have three little ones, so...

204
00:09:33,825 --> 00:09:35,702
Oh, exciting!
What are you guys talking about?

205
00:09:35,785 --> 00:09:37,704
Sylvia asked me to babysit her kids.

206
00:09:40,540 --> 00:09:43,418
It just... [stammers]
It just came up. I-I wasn't even...

207
00:09:43,501 --> 00:09:44,502
I'm so excited.

208
00:09:44,586 --> 00:09:47,005
Good. Yeah. That'll... That'll... Hmm.

209
00:09:47,589 --> 00:09:49,174
- Um...
- [chuckles]

210
00:09:49,257 --> 00:09:52,469
You were asking where the restroom was.
Uh, let me just walk you back there.

211
00:09:52,552 --> 00:09:55,055
It's a maze here.
I'll be right back. Okay? Yeah.

212
00:09:55,138 --> 00:09:57,682
- Two seconds. Um, I'll be back.
- Okay.

213
00:09:57,766 --> 00:09:59,935
- She might be a while.
- [chuckles]

214
00:10:02,312 --> 00:10:04,731
I knew you were going to
do something fucked up like this.

215
00:10:04,814 --> 00:10:06,566
- What are you talking about?
- What am I talking about?

216
00:10:06,608 --> 00:10:09,208
We've been here for five minutes,
and Peyton is now your employee.

217
00:10:09,277 --> 00:10:10,278
That is very weird.

218
00:10:10,362 --> 00:10:12,530
I don't think it's weird,
and Peyton doesn't think it's weird,

219
00:10:12,572 --> 00:10:14,282
so maybe believe women.

220
00:10:14,366 --> 00:10:18,203
Not the right use of that expression, FYI.
Don't toss that around like that!

221
00:10:18,286 --> 00:10:20,455
- Why are you freaking out?
- You think she's too young for me.

222
00:10:20,497 --> 00:10:22,290
That thought never even crossed my mind.

223
00:10:22,374 --> 00:10:24,251
She's a millennial. I'm a millennial.

224
00:10:24,334 --> 00:10:27,879
We are on different ends of the millennial
spectrum, but we are both millennials.

225
00:10:27,963 --> 00:10:31,299
We are bookend millennials,
and that is very romantic, I think.

226
00:10:31,383 --> 00:10:32,842
I hear Joe Biden's a millennial.

227
00:10:32,926 --> 00:10:37,138
Our age difference is not that big a deal,
all right? We have a very deep connection.

228
00:10:37,222 --> 00:10:40,183
And she... I don't know if you've noticed,
but she's a very old soul.

229
00:10:40,267 --> 00:10:41,601
I think she's adorable.

230
00:10:41,685 --> 00:10:45,063
She literally said she was a babysitter.
I needed a babysitter. That was it!

231
00:10:45,146 --> 00:10:47,732
Now I'm honestly just very confused.
Did you just hire her to be nice?

232
00:10:47,774 --> 00:10:50,318
Yes! I-I think she's so cute and sweet,

233
00:10:50,402 --> 00:10:52,570
- and funny and...
- Stop saying she's cute and sweet, okay?

234
00:10:52,612 --> 00:10:53,821
- Why?
- She's not a troll doll.

235
00:10:53,863 --> 00:10:56,074
She's my girlfriend, all right?
It's a little condescending.

236
00:10:56,116 --> 00:10:58,368
I think she's great.
But if you want me to "unhire" her...

237
00:10:58,410 --> 00:11:01,121
No, 'cause now that would be even weirder,
all right?

238
00:11:01,204 --> 00:11:02,247
You have a new babysitter.

239
00:11:02,330 --> 00:11:03,748
- Congratulations.
- Okay.

240
00:11:04,749 --> 00:11:06,585
Oh, it's so nice to be out for dinner.

241
00:11:07,544 --> 00:11:09,462
Charlie's only been gone for 52 hours,

242
00:11:10,297 --> 00:11:13,008
and I'm just so sick
of eating dino nuggets and fish sticks.

243
00:11:13,091 --> 00:11:14,384
- Mmm. No.
- No.

244
00:11:14,467 --> 00:11:15,468
[phone buzzes]

245
00:11:16,428 --> 00:11:20,098
Peyton keeps texting me
the cutest photos. It's so annoying.

246
00:11:20,181 --> 00:11:23,351
- Aw, Simon's got a girlfriend. Aw.
- Right?

247
00:11:23,435 --> 00:11:26,062
She really speaks to eight-year-old boys
and 40-year-old men.

248
00:11:26,146 --> 00:11:27,314
Basically the same thing.

249
00:11:27,397 --> 00:11:29,691
I don't wanna go home.
Should we order some more dessert?

250
00:11:29,774 --> 00:11:31,985
We have had everything on the menu.

251
00:11:32,068 --> 00:11:34,905
Well, let's get some more wine
or, like, a cheese plate.

252
00:11:35,530 --> 00:11:39,784
Please, please. I don't want to have to go
home and make conversation with this girl.

253
00:11:39,868 --> 00:11:40,702
It's a punish.

254
00:11:40,785 --> 00:11:43,496
You made your weird bed,
and now you have to lie in it.

255
00:11:43,580 --> 00:11:45,540
- No sympathy?
- None.

256
00:11:49,002 --> 00:11:50,462
- Hey.
- [Peyton] Hey.

257
00:11:50,545 --> 00:11:51,838
How was dinner?

258
00:11:51,922 --> 00:11:55,258
Oh, it was really nice. Thank you.
Thanks for asking. How were the kids?

259
00:11:55,342 --> 00:11:58,887
- Ugh, so adorable. Seriously the sweetest.
- Aw.

260
00:11:58,970 --> 00:11:59,971
So easy to put to sleep.

261
00:12:00,055 --> 00:12:03,099
Aw, well… [sucks teeth]
…thank you so much.

262
00:12:03,183 --> 00:12:05,393
- Thank you. [chuckles]
- Yeah.

263
00:12:05,477 --> 00:12:11,691
[yawns] Oh, my goodness. Think this week
has just caught up with me. [sighs]

264
00:12:11,775 --> 00:12:13,193
Do you have a second to talk?

265
00:12:14,319 --> 00:12:16,238
Yeah. Oh, God. I'd love nothing more.

266
00:12:16,321 --> 00:12:18,448
- [chuckles, clears throat]
- [chuckles]

267
00:12:21,618 --> 00:12:23,787
So, you and Will go way back, right?

268
00:12:23,870 --> 00:12:27,499
We do, yeah.
Known each other for over 20 years.

269
00:12:27,582 --> 00:12:30,752
He's tough to read. Like,
I don't know what's going on sometimes.

270
00:12:30,835 --> 00:12:32,045
Mmm.

271
00:12:32,128 --> 00:12:36,550
Anyways, I've got a birthday coming up,
and it's kind of a big one.

272
00:12:37,133 --> 00:12:38,385
The big two-six.

273
00:12:38,468 --> 00:12:40,220
Oh! Congratulations.

274
00:12:40,303 --> 00:12:42,097
My friends
are throwing me a birthday party.

275
00:12:42,180 --> 00:12:46,142
And I was thinking, I don't know, I kinda…

276
00:12:46,685 --> 00:12:49,312
- What? You want...
- …want Will to be there.

277
00:12:50,146 --> 00:12:52,524
- I want him to meet my friends.
- Hmm. 'Course.

278
00:12:52,607 --> 00:12:55,402
Anyways, the theme is YOLO.
Do you know what that means?

279
00:12:55,485 --> 00:12:57,279
- I do.
- It means "you only live once."

280
00:12:57,362 --> 00:13:00,031
Mmm. It's interesting. It's a good idea.

281
00:13:00,115 --> 00:13:02,284
- It's the first letter of all those words.
- I see.

282
00:13:02,367 --> 00:13:03,785
It means just going for it,

283
00:13:03,868 --> 00:13:06,246
- because you've only got this one life.
- Yeah, I get it.

284
00:13:06,329 --> 00:13:08,999
So, do you think
Will would be okay with that?

285
00:13:09,082 --> 00:13:11,668
Like, merging our worlds
at my birthday party.

286
00:13:12,627 --> 00:13:14,713
I... You could just ask him.

287
00:13:16,047 --> 00:13:17,424
What do you think he's gonna say?

288
00:13:19,175 --> 00:13:22,762
I don't know. I mean, I think he's still
getting himself together from the divorce.

289
00:13:22,846 --> 00:13:26,224
I know he seems like he's together,
but he's still dealing with the fallout.

290
00:13:26,808 --> 00:13:30,395
Audrey's totally moved on. I mean,
her and Skaagn just went to Norway.

291
00:13:31,187 --> 00:13:33,690
What? What? How do you know them?

292
00:13:33,773 --> 00:13:35,609
- Instagram. I follow them.
- Oh.

293
00:13:39,946 --> 00:13:42,115
Ugh, braids. Of course.

294
00:13:42,198 --> 00:13:44,367
Right? So obvi.

295
00:13:48,663 --> 00:13:51,958
Do you think Will's still, like,
in love with her?

296
00:13:53,043 --> 00:13:56,129
I... Absolutely not. But I do think
he's still getting himself together.

297
00:13:56,213 --> 00:14:00,592
So, if he ends up
not wanting to merge worlds at your party,

298
00:14:00,675 --> 00:14:01,885
it's got nothing to do with you.

299
00:14:01,927 --> 00:14:03,220
"Merge worlds" sounds cool.

300
00:14:04,137 --> 00:14:05,138
[chuckles] Yeah.

301
00:14:06,473 --> 00:14:07,593
I'm gonna stick with "YOLO."

302
00:14:08,642 --> 00:14:10,644
It's a great... It's a great theme.

303
00:14:11,686 --> 00:14:14,356
Okay. Well, thank you again.

304
00:14:14,439 --> 00:14:16,149
- Sure.
- Thank you.

305
00:14:16,233 --> 00:14:18,318
[slurping]

306
00:14:19,778 --> 00:14:21,905
And did you just...
Did you get a spot at the front?

307
00:14:25,200 --> 00:14:26,201
[buzzes]

308
00:14:29,371 --> 00:14:31,248
[buzzing]

309
00:14:31,331 --> 00:14:34,417
[sighing]

310
00:14:37,212 --> 00:14:40,090
[knocking]

311
00:14:43,260 --> 00:14:46,260
- My children are sleeping. [shushes]
- Okay, look, we need to talk right...

312
00:14:46,304 --> 00:14:47,722
- [whispering] We need to talk.
- Backyard.

313
00:14:47,764 --> 00:14:48,932
Okay, fine.

314
00:14:51,351 --> 00:14:52,435
Okay.

315
00:14:56,982 --> 00:14:58,024
[sighs]

316
00:15:00,819 --> 00:15:02,195
I demand an apology.

317
00:15:02,279 --> 00:15:03,822
What? What are you talking about?

318
00:15:03,905 --> 00:15:06,283
'Cause you told Peyton
that I am still in love with Audrey.

319
00:15:06,366 --> 00:15:09,869
- [scoffs] Okay. Uh, I-I didn't.
- You did not say that?

320
00:15:09,953 --> 00:15:11,746
- Mm-mmm.
- She was just at my house freaking out

321
00:15:11,788 --> 00:15:14,874
'cause she said that you said
that I was still in love with Audrey,

322
00:15:14,958 --> 00:15:16,584
and I was not ready for
a "real relationship."

323
00:15:16,626 --> 00:15:18,253
- I didn't say that.
- You didn't?

324
00:15:18,336 --> 00:15:19,296
No, I didn't.

325
00:15:19,379 --> 00:15:21,840
I said to her that you might need
to take it slow,

326
00:15:21,923 --> 00:15:24,634
because you're still recovering from
the divorce,

327
00:15:24,718 --> 00:15:27,304
but that's no reflection on
how much you care for her.

328
00:15:27,387 --> 00:15:30,765
- Why are you saying anything to her?
- Because she asked me directly.

329
00:15:30,849 --> 00:15:32,893
You are trying to
undermine my relationship.

330
00:15:32,976 --> 00:15:34,895
I'm not. I'm not. [stammers]

331
00:15:34,978 --> 00:15:38,440
- I like Peyton. She's adorable. She's...
- This "adorable" shit again.

332
00:15:38,523 --> 00:15:39,566
Stop saying that!

333
00:15:39,649 --> 00:15:41,693
You think that she's too young for me,

334
00:15:41,776 --> 00:15:45,280
and instead of just saying that
to my face, you made her your babysitter.

335
00:15:45,363 --> 00:15:46,364
Okay, you're right.

336
00:15:46,448 --> 00:15:49,033
I do think she's too young for you,
because she is too young for you.

337
00:15:49,075 --> 00:15:51,536
And a lot of women would get
a little bit offended

338
00:15:51,620 --> 00:15:55,081
seeing this guy your age
dating someone so much younger.

339
00:15:55,165 --> 00:15:58,960
Well, what I would say to those women is
that I don't have a choice who I meet.

340
00:15:59,044 --> 00:16:00,670
- I'm a bartender. I meet young people.
- What?

341
00:16:00,712 --> 00:16:02,964
Oh, you know who else meets young people?
College professors.

342
00:16:03,006 --> 00:16:04,883
Boy Scout troop leaders. Priests.

343
00:16:04,966 --> 00:16:08,720
- I take extreme umbrage at that comment.
- It's a great group.

344
00:16:08,803 --> 00:16:11,473
- I take the most umbrage one can take.
- Oh.

345
00:16:11,556 --> 00:16:13,058
You are being so judgmental of me.

346
00:16:13,141 --> 00:16:15,477
Of course I'm judgmental,
because it's pathetic.

347
00:16:15,560 --> 00:16:19,773
We have a very beautiful,
deep, meaningful connection.

348
00:16:19,856 --> 00:16:20,940
Okay, that... You know what?

349
00:16:20,982 --> 00:16:23,818
No matter what you say, Will,
you're too old for her. Okay?

350
00:16:23,902 --> 00:16:27,989
You know, anything that doesn't conform
to your 2.3 kids,

351
00:16:28,073 --> 00:16:33,078
white picket fence lifestyle really...
R-really gets under your skin, doesn't it?

352
00:16:33,161 --> 00:16:36,122
How dare you lecture me when you haven't
even said congratulations on my new job.

353
00:16:36,164 --> 00:16:37,832
Not one. Not one single question.

354
00:16:37,916 --> 00:16:39,876
You know what a big deal it is
for me to go back to work.

355
00:16:39,918 --> 00:16:42,170
I'm dealing with my own shit. I don't
give a fuck about that right now.

356
00:16:42,212 --> 00:16:44,088
Yeah, you've made it really clear, Will.
I get it.

357
00:16:44,130 --> 00:16:45,381
You really got in my head about this.

358
00:16:45,423 --> 00:16:47,050
Now all I can think of
is what's wrong with her.

359
00:16:47,092 --> 00:16:49,469
All I want is for you to end up happy,
you fucking idiot!

360
00:16:49,553 --> 00:16:51,638
Well, I am fucking happy.
So, congratulations.

361
00:16:51,721 --> 00:16:53,515
I've never been fucking happier
in my life!

362
00:16:56,768 --> 00:16:57,686
[groans]

363
00:16:58,186 --> 00:16:59,271
Oh, my God. Are you okay?

364
00:16:59,354 --> 00:17:02,232
[groaning]

365
00:17:02,315 --> 00:17:04,066
- [Sylvia] Whoa.
- [breathing heavily]

366
00:17:04,150 --> 00:17:06,361
[Sylvia] Oh, no. Oh.

367
00:17:08,029 --> 00:17:09,447
Send me the invoice.

368
00:17:11,491 --> 00:17:13,368
Dad's gonna be pissed.

369
00:17:14,244 --> 00:17:15,411
How long have you been there?

370
00:17:34,973 --> 00:17:36,224
[buzzes]

371
00:17:36,308 --> 00:17:37,434
[door buzzes]

372
00:17:44,399 --> 00:17:46,568
- Can I help you?
- Is Peyton here?

373
00:17:46,651 --> 00:17:49,404
Hey, Peyton.
There's some guy here to see you.

374
00:17:49,487 --> 00:17:51,364
Hey. Oh, my God.
What happened to your face?

375
00:17:51,448 --> 00:17:53,867
I, uh, walked into a glass door.

376
00:17:53,950 --> 00:17:57,787
I'm fine. Look, I'm going to throw you
the most epic birthday party ever.

377
00:17:57,871 --> 00:18:00,415
I'm gonna shut down Lucky Penny. Open bar.

378
00:18:00,498 --> 00:18:02,584
Invite all your friends. [stammers]
We'll blow it out, okay?

379
00:18:02,626 --> 00:18:05,211
Are you sure? I don't wanna force you
to do something you're not ready to do.

380
00:18:05,253 --> 00:18:07,714
I'm ready. I'm ready to do this, okay?
I love you.

381
00:18:07,797 --> 00:18:10,342
[inhales sharply]
I didn't mean to say that.

382
00:18:11,009 --> 00:18:13,762
- It's fine.
- That was a mistake.

383
00:18:13,845 --> 00:18:15,680
Mmm, I didn't mean to say that.

384
00:18:15,764 --> 00:18:18,141
That w... That slipped out. I'm, uh... I...

385
00:18:18,225 --> 00:18:20,894
- I... I care about you deeply, but I-I...
- It's fine.

386
00:18:20,977 --> 00:18:22,437
I was married. We say "I love you" a lot.

387
00:18:22,479 --> 00:18:24,397
- I'm used to tossing it around.
- Yeah. I get it.

388
00:18:24,439 --> 00:18:27,776
- We can just pretend that didn't happen.
- Fantastic! Maybe one day, yeah. Great.

389
00:18:27,859 --> 00:18:29,444
- Okay, thank you. [chuckles]
- [chuckles]

390
00:18:29,486 --> 00:18:32,656
- Best birthday present ever.
- It's gonna be so fun. [chuckles] Yeah.

391
00:18:32,739 --> 00:18:34,616
- Uh…
- Yeah?

392
00:18:34,699 --> 00:18:36,576
- [whispering] Question.
- Yeah.

393
00:18:37,661 --> 00:18:40,330
This man on your couch, who is he?

394
00:18:40,413 --> 00:18:42,999
That's Alan. He's our new roommate.

395
00:18:43,083 --> 00:18:46,336
Alan is in his mid-to-late-50s?

396
00:18:47,003 --> 00:18:48,129
Alan's 29.

397
00:18:48,213 --> 00:18:50,090
No, no, no, no, no.

398
00:18:50,757 --> 00:18:54,511
- What?
- Alan is not 29. That's not true.

399
00:18:54,594 --> 00:18:56,137
Alan is a senior citizen.

400
00:18:57,556 --> 00:18:58,848
Did somebody say "party"?

401
00:18:59,808 --> 00:19:01,434
Hey, well,
if you want some help tomorrow, um,

402
00:19:01,476 --> 00:19:04,563
pulling images, making a mood board,
kinda my thing.

403
00:19:04,646 --> 00:19:05,647
Yeah.

404
00:19:06,648 --> 00:19:08,650
So,
I wanted to talk you guys about something

405
00:19:08,733 --> 00:19:10,944
that's going to be
a big change around here.

406
00:19:11,027 --> 00:19:13,029
Are you and Dad getting divorced?

407
00:19:13,113 --> 00:19:15,865
What? No. I'm going back to work.

408
00:19:15,949 --> 00:19:18,910
- Cool. Latesies. [sighs]
- No. Please sit down. Thank you.

409
00:19:18,994 --> 00:19:21,329
As I said, I'm going back to work.

410
00:19:21,413 --> 00:19:23,290
- As what?
- As a lawyer.

411
00:19:23,373 --> 00:19:25,834
You're a lawyer?
I thought Dad was a lawyer.

412
00:19:25,917 --> 00:19:27,961
Yes, Dad is a lawyer,
and I used to be a lawyer.

413
00:19:28,044 --> 00:19:29,170
Told you this many times.

414
00:19:29,254 --> 00:19:31,089
So, you're going to work for Dad.

415
00:19:31,172 --> 00:19:33,174
No, I'm going to work at my own job.

416
00:19:33,258 --> 00:19:36,428
It's important to me for you guys to see
that women also work

417
00:19:36,511 --> 00:19:39,723
and contribute to their communities
and their families just like men do.

418
00:19:39,806 --> 00:19:43,476
So, it'll be a transition for all of us,
but, uh, we'll get through it.

419
00:19:44,477 --> 00:19:45,478
Any questions?

420
00:19:46,479 --> 00:19:48,732
- We're out of Oreos.
- What?

421
00:19:48,815 --> 00:19:50,859
You said to write down
when we need things, and I did.

422
00:19:50,901 --> 00:19:52,694
- Okay.
- But we're still out of Oreos.

423
00:19:52,777 --> 00:19:53,778
Okay. Okay.

424
00:19:57,198 --> 00:19:58,617
Oh, my God. Is that from Peyton?

425
00:19:58,700 --> 00:19:59,784
No, it's from Will.

426
00:19:59,868 --> 00:20:03,455
But it's about Peyton's birthday party.
Please, can we go?

427
00:20:03,538 --> 00:20:05,206
No, honey, it's at a bar.

428
00:20:05,290 --> 00:20:08,877
Oh, my God. I loved her. She was
the best babysitter we've ever had.

429
00:20:08,960 --> 00:20:11,463
She looks exactly like Billie Eilish.
[chuckles]

430
00:20:12,130 --> 00:20:14,007
"YOLO" means "you only live once."

431
00:20:14,758 --> 00:20:15,800
Uh, yes. I'm aware.

432
00:20:15,884 --> 00:20:17,260
- Oreos.
- Got it.

433
00:20:19,638 --> 00:20:22,182
What the fuck is going on? It's Saturday
and you closed the bar?

434
00:20:22,265 --> 00:20:24,142
Will didn't tell you?
He decided to shut down the bar

435
00:20:24,184 --> 00:20:26,477
on the most profitable night
of the week to throw a birthday party

436
00:20:26,519 --> 00:20:28,563
for his new girlfriend, Bedazzled Pants.

437
00:20:28,647 --> 00:20:31,066
Anything we lose tonight, William,
it's on you, bro.

438
00:20:31,149 --> 00:20:33,610
- This is the whole point in owning a bar.
- No, it's not.

439
00:20:33,693 --> 00:20:35,612
- Point of owning a bar is to make money.
- Thank you.

440
00:20:35,654 --> 00:20:39,741
Hey. Wow. I didn't think you'd come.

441
00:20:39,824 --> 00:20:43,078
Yeah. Well, I mean, as they say,
"You only turn 26 once."

442
00:20:43,161 --> 00:20:45,288
- Very true. If you're lucky. [chuckles]
- Yeah.

443
00:20:45,372 --> 00:20:47,499
- Uh, well, I'm glad you came.
- I like Peyton.

444
00:20:48,625 --> 00:20:50,168
- How's your door?
- How's your face?

445
00:20:50,252 --> 00:20:52,545
I'm wearing a lot of makeup.
A lot of cover-up. Can you tell?

446
00:20:52,587 --> 00:20:54,214
- The blending is impeccable.
- Pretty good, yeah.

447
00:20:54,256 --> 00:20:55,966
- Peyton helped me.
- She's got skills.

448
00:20:56,049 --> 00:20:58,969
- Sylvia!
- Hey! Ah. Happy birthday.

449
00:20:59,052 --> 00:21:00,845
- [Peyton] Thanks for coming.
- Of course. YOLO!

450
00:21:00,887 --> 00:21:02,889
- Yes, YOLO. That's what we say.
- YOLO!

451
00:21:02,973 --> 00:21:04,224
YOLO!

452
00:21:04,307 --> 00:21:06,100
- It's so good to see you.
- Yo, this party is lit.

453
00:21:06,142 --> 00:21:07,561
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

454
00:21:07,644 --> 00:21:11,147
- This is my roommate Alan, Sylvia.
- Oh. Yeah. Good. Nice to meet you.

455
00:21:11,231 --> 00:21:12,524
Oh, Peyton, let's get a picture.

456
00:21:12,607 --> 00:21:14,192
- Sorry. Gotta go.
- Yeah.

457
00:21:14,276 --> 00:21:17,487
Alan, we were just talking.
Do you remember where you were on 9/11?

458
00:21:17,571 --> 00:21:19,281
Ah, I'll never forget.

459
00:21:19,364 --> 00:21:23,618
I was in my third-grade classroom,
because I was eight. Excuse me.

460
00:21:24,744 --> 00:21:26,288
Guy says he's 29.

461
00:21:26,371 --> 00:21:28,748
- Come on.
- If he's 29, call Make-A-Wish.

462
00:21:28,832 --> 00:21:30,000
Yeah. [chuckles]

463
00:21:30,083 --> 00:21:32,419
Hey, everyone. I'm Riley.

464
00:21:32,502 --> 00:21:33,670
I've known Peyton since…

465
00:21:33,753 --> 00:21:35,255
- Riley's great.
- Yeah.

466
00:21:35,338 --> 00:21:37,132
Yeah. Riley works at Baskin-Robbins

467
00:21:37,215 --> 00:21:39,092
if you want a free milkshake or something.

468
00:21:39,175 --> 00:21:40,510
YOLO!

469
00:21:40,594 --> 00:21:42,053
[Peyton's friends cheer] YOLO! Whoo!

470
00:21:42,137 --> 00:21:43,388
YOLO is empowering.

471
00:21:43,471 --> 00:21:45,473
Here's our favorite song from high school.

472
00:21:45,557 --> 00:21:48,393
- No. Oh, my God. No.
- Too late! It's too late!

473
00:21:48,476 --> 00:21:49,644
[imitates explosion]

474
00:21:49,728 --> 00:21:51,104
["Starships" playing]

475
00:21:51,187 --> 00:21:53,565
Did they say this is their favorite song
from high school?

476
00:21:54,065 --> 00:21:55,901
- They did.
- Wow.

477
00:21:56,776 --> 00:21:58,695
[mouthing words to "Starships"]

478
00:22:02,282 --> 00:22:03,283
[Peyton] So great.

479
00:22:25,013 --> 00:22:26,181
What am I doing?

480
00:22:26,264 --> 00:22:27,265
That.

481
00:22:29,684 --> 00:22:31,645
- I'm a cliché.
- What?

482
00:22:31,728 --> 00:22:32,729
[song continues]

483
00:22:34,856 --> 00:22:35,857
Oh, no.

484
00:22:35,941 --> 00:22:37,484
[Sylvia] What? What's wrong?

485
00:22:37,567 --> 00:22:39,903
- Oh, I gotta get out of this.
- What?

486
00:22:39,986 --> 00:22:41,786
Oh, you were right.
I gotta break up with her.

487
00:22:41,863 --> 00:22:43,281
I have to break up with her right now.

488
00:22:43,323 --> 00:22:45,200
- Not tonight. It's her birthday.
- I have to do it tonight.

489
00:22:45,242 --> 00:22:46,785
Will you help me do it tonight?

490
00:22:46,868 --> 00:22:47,994
- Absolutely not.
- You have to help.

491
00:22:48,036 --> 00:22:49,954
Will you say we're having an affair?
A steamy affair?

492
00:22:49,996 --> 00:22:51,756
- Please? Oh, God.
- I will not say that. No.

493
00:22:53,750 --> 00:22:56,211
I thought you said you had a connection,
that she was an old soul.

494
00:22:56,253 --> 00:22:58,373
She's not an old soul.
Look what the fuck she's doing.

495
00:22:59,381 --> 00:23:03,134
Are you kidding me? Oh, God.
Oh, I'm gonna be alone forever.

496
00:23:03,218 --> 00:23:06,346
No, you're not. You're not.
At least you haven't been together long.

497
00:23:06,429 --> 00:23:08,139
Come on, man. You'll be all right.

498
00:23:08,223 --> 00:23:10,934
You'll meet someone
who's more on your wavelength,

499
00:23:11,017 --> 00:23:14,646
who's smart and funny,
and who's a better match.

500
00:23:14,729 --> 00:23:16,898
[mouthing words to "Starships"]

501
00:23:16,982 --> 00:23:18,400
You don't have to stay. You can go.

502
00:23:18,483 --> 00:23:20,883
You kidding me? I got all dressed up.
I'm not going anywhere.

503
00:23:23,238 --> 00:23:25,740
I am... Wait. That you're happy
makes me feel like... [chuckles]

504
00:23:25,782 --> 00:23:27,450
All right. Look. Did we get her look?

505
00:23:27,534 --> 00:23:28,618
I was really happy.

506
00:23:28,702 --> 00:23:30,954
[Maddie] No! The thing she was wearing...
She looked so dumb.

507
00:23:30,996 --> 00:23:35,333
No, I don't think it was... I'm dumb.
I mean, I think that she looked good.

508
00:23:35,417 --> 00:23:38,211
- I did not invite her. Did you invite her?
- I invited everyone.

509
00:23:39,462 --> 00:23:41,214
- [Maddie] Oh, he's cute.
- [Alan, Maddie chuckle]

510
00:23:41,256 --> 00:23:46,595
That was the best birthday
of my entire life. All thanks to you.

511
00:23:48,680 --> 00:23:49,681
What's up?

512
00:23:51,433 --> 00:23:53,685
Maybe we should just sit down
and talk for a second.

513
00:23:54,853 --> 00:23:58,523
- Uh-oh.
- [chuckles] Just close the door.

514
00:24:00,442 --> 00:24:01,342
[Peyton chuckles]

515
00:24:01,401 --> 00:24:03,778
[sighs]

516
00:24:05,196 --> 00:24:06,698
[chuckles] What?

517
00:24:08,700 --> 00:24:11,912
I hate to be doing this tonight, but I...

518
00:24:14,831 --> 00:24:19,669
I just don't think we're, like, great
for each other, especially right now.

519
00:24:19,753 --> 00:24:23,089
You know, you're so young. You have
so much of your life ahead of you.

520
00:24:23,173 --> 00:24:29,095
And I'm... I'm so old, and I'm dealing with
this boring, old-guy shit.

521
00:24:29,179 --> 00:24:30,555
You know, it's just...

522
00:24:30,639 --> 00:24:34,142
[chuckles] Are you breaking up with me
on my birthday?

523
00:24:34,768 --> 00:24:39,314
I am. And I really... I just think it's...
It's probably for the best, you know?

524
00:24:39,397 --> 00:24:40,398
[scoffs]

525
00:24:42,067 --> 00:24:44,903
And I just, you know...
I wanna make sure you're gonna be okay,

526
00:24:44,986 --> 00:24:48,406
so, like, if you want me to stay over
or something like that, I'm more than…

527
00:24:48,490 --> 00:24:50,784
[scoffs] Why the fuck would I want that?

528
00:24:52,077 --> 00:24:54,537
Just in case you didn't wanna be alone
or something like that.

529
00:24:55,830 --> 00:24:58,166
I don't even really think
this deserves a breakup.

530
00:24:59,459 --> 00:25:01,336
- Really?
- Yeah.

531
00:25:01,962 --> 00:25:02,963
Oh.

532
00:25:05,715 --> 00:25:06,716
[sighs]

533
00:25:06,800 --> 00:25:07,884
Where are you going?

534
00:25:08,593 --> 00:25:12,222
To meet my friends. It's my birthday.
I just came back here 'cause you're old.

535
00:25:17,102 --> 00:25:19,271
- Let's go to Riley's, you guys.
- Oh, fuck yes!

536
00:25:19,354 --> 00:25:20,772
The boogie don't quit! [grunts]

537
00:25:20,855 --> 00:25:21,982
[Maddie] I'll call an Uber.

538
00:25:23,066 --> 00:25:26,361
Look, I'm-I'm...
I'm really sorry it went down like this.

539
00:25:28,029 --> 00:25:29,030
Nighty night.

540
00:25:29,114 --> 00:25:31,074
You shut the fuck up, old man, okay?

541
00:25:31,157 --> 00:25:33,034
- Okay, boomer.
- Don't you "boomer" me.

542
00:25:33,118 --> 00:25:34,744
You are old. You're an old man!

543
00:25:34,828 --> 00:25:36,496
Your generation destroyed the environment.

544
00:25:36,538 --> 00:25:39,040
You will die before me.
You have osteoporosis.

545
00:25:39,124 --> 00:25:41,376
- You've shrunk since I've known you.
- Try dressing your age.

546
00:25:41,418 --> 00:25:42,711
Look out for this fucking guy.

547
00:25:42,794 --> 00:25:43,712
You dress your age.

548
00:25:43,795 --> 00:25:45,547
Get a top hat and a monocle and, uh,

549
00:25:45,630 --> 00:25:47,966
one of those bikes
with one big wheel, motherfucker.

550
00:25:48,049 --> 00:25:49,259
Go take your Lipitor!

551
00:25:49,342 --> 00:25:53,889
Oh, you old fuck. You fucking old
motherfucker. [breathes deeply]

552
00:25:54,848 --> 00:25:57,851
[Peyton, Maddie, Alan laughing]

553
00:26:05,817 --> 00:26:07,819
["We Are Young" playing]
